Anthony Joshua’s much anticipated rematch with Oleksandr Usyk could now be in serious doubt due to Russia’s invasion of Ukraine last week. Joshua is currently gearing up for a rematch with Oleksandr Usyk, but Russia’s invasion of Usyk’s home country, Ukraine, may cause uncertainties regarding that bout as Usyk recently posted pictures showing geared up to fight with other members of the Kyiv Territorial Defence. The fight is set to take place in the late spring or early summer although no date or venue has been set. And Usyk has returned to his homeland following its invasion by Russian forces, publicly decrying the war and pleading with Vladimir Putin to end the fighting.   Coppa Italia, Copa del Rey semis Live on StarTimes     African Fencing:  Nigeria outshine South Africa, Senegal      Emirates FA Cup Fifth Round Proper to air live on DSTV,…   The 35-year-old father-of-three has joined best friend and two-time Olympic champ Vasiliy Lomachenko and legendary heavyweight brothers Wladimir and Kyiv mayor Vitali Klitschko in swapping gloves for guns. Meanwhile, Joshua has firmly put himself in Dillian Whyte’s corner for his WBC world heavyweight title fight against Tyson Fury – even though he ‘hates him’. Fury will look to defend his title against the Body Snatcher Whyte at Wembley on April 23, after the highly-anticipated all-British showdown was finally agreed following weeks of speculation. “I’m rooting for Dillian, even though I hate him, and I want to smash him one of these days. “Go on Dillian, I’m with you all the way.”